```rust
/// Override the default `.vc-config.toml` write (POR only).
///
/// - Absent: write the canned `VC_CONFIG_APP_ONLY`.
/// - `--config none`: skip writing.
/// - `--config <path>`: copy the file at `<path>` to
///   `.vc-config.toml`.
#[arg(long = "config", value_name = "none|PATH")]
pub config: Option<String>,  // raw; consumer calls parse_config_kind(s, default)
```

Holding the raw string at the arg layer keeps the parser's
`default` parameter at the call site (where init's POR canned
default lives) rather than forcing a static closure adapter.
Substep 3 may revise — e.g. closure-wrapping the parser as a
clap `value_parser` if a single static default is acceptable
for all consumers — but the raw-string + consumer-side parse
shape is the simplest fit for the Option-A signature.

Optional on the command line so scripts and bots can be
explicit while interactive use stays lazy.

